  "source": "learn",
  "type": "mcq",
  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "How do you use function notation f(x)?",
  "reading": "<p><strong>Function notation</strong> \\( \\text{f}(x) \\) names a rule: it reads \"f of \\( x \\)\" and tells you what to do to the input \\( x \\). To <strong>evaluate</strong> \\( \\text{f}(3) \\), substitute \\( 3 \\) for every \\( x \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — given \\( \\text{f}(x) = 2x^2 - 5x + 1 \\), find \\( \\text{f}(3) \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Replace every \\( x \\) with \\( 3 \\): \\( \\text{f}(3) = 2(3)^2 - 5(3) + 1 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Powers first: \\( (3)^2 = 9 \\), so \\( 2 \\times 9 = 18 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Then \\( -5 \\times 3 = -15 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Add up: \\( 18 - 15 + 1 = 4 \\), so \\[ \\text{f}(3) = 4. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Watch negatives: \\( \\text{f}(-2) = 2(-2)^2 - 5(-2) + 1 = 8 + 10 + 1 = 19 \\). A squared negative is positive, and subtracting a negative adds.</p>",
