  "readingTitle": "What do a zero index and a negative index mean?",
  "reading": "<p>These two rules follow directly from the division law.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Zero index:</strong> \\( a^m \\div a^m = a^{0} \\), but anything divided by itself is \\( 1 \\), so \\[ a^0 = 1 \\quad (a \\neq 0). \\] Every non-zero base to the power zero is \\( 1 \\) — not \\( 0 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Negative index:</strong> a minus sign in the index means \"take the <strong>reciprocal</strong>\": \\[ a^{-n} = \\frac{1}{a^{n}}. \\] It does <em>not</em> make the answer negative.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — evaluate \\( 2^{-3} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. The negative index means take the reciprocal: \\( 2^{-3} = \\dfrac{1}{2^{3}} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Work out the positive power: \\( 2^3 = 8 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. So \\[ 2^{-3} = \\frac{1}{8}. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The answer \\( \\tfrac{1}{8} \\) is positive — a negative index never means a negative number.</p>",
