  "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Rationalising \\( \\dfrac{1}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\) by multiplying by \\( \\dfrac{2 + \\sqrt{3}}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> You must use the CONJUGATE (opposite sign). A weak answer keeps \\( 2 + \\sqrt{3} \\) and does not clear the surd; a strong answer multiplies by \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\), giving denominator \\( 4 - 3 = 1 \\) and answer \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\).</p>",
